User Manual for Town Names NML Generator

Town Names NML Generator is a Lua-based GUI application that generates NML code for Town Name NewGRFs for OpenTTD.

It is designed for users with little or no experience with NML or coding. Its main goal is to make the town name generation process easy to understand, even for complete beginners.

This manual provides a short overview of how town name generation works in OpenTTD just enough to help you understand what the tool does and how to use it.
For more detailed information, see the following resources:

  • TT-Wiki: Town names
  • TT-Wiki: Town names parts

How do Town names work?

There are two types of town name sets:

  1. One long list of complete names (often real-world locations); limited to ~32,000 names
  2. Several lists of name parts, combined into names during in-game map generation

Note: Since the first case is a subset of the second, this manual focuses on a practical example of creating the slightly more complex compound names.

Each item in a list can have a probability assigned to it. For example, the following adjectival modifiers:

Little , 2
North , 1
Old , 1

As you can see, the probabilities are not expressed as percentages, but as weights. The sum of these weights is 4, so they can be interpreted as:

Little , 2/4 = 50 %
North , 1/4 = 25 %
Old , 1/4 = 25 %

Providing probabilities is recommended (especially for compound name parts), but they are optional. If omitted, the application automatically assigns a value of 1 to all missing probabilities.

Using the app

The workflow is demonstrated using an example town name set that combines four parts into a random compound name.

Note: The files used in this example are located in the _example folder included with the application.

Step 1 Prepare source data

Before starting the app, prepare the names you want to process.
You can use Notepad, MS Excel, or similar tools, but the names have to be saved as plain text, ideally as *.txt or *.csv.

By design, Town Names NML Generator is NOT a text editor. It can only read text files and display their contents; all edits must be made in external software of your choice.

The input data can be either a simple list of names (one name per line) or a list of comma-separated pairs in the form <name>, <weighted probability>.

This is the content of the four example CSV files:

  part1.csv:          part2.csv:          part3.csv:            part4.csv: 
                                                                           
  , 50                Clay,1              ville,5               , 50       
  North ,1            River,1             town,1                Bay,1     
  Old ,1              Stone,1             ford,1                Falls,1   
  New ,1              Pine,3              ton,5                 Ridge,1   
  Fort ,1             Ash,1               ham,1                 Harbor,1  
  Port ,1             Cedar,1             stead,1               Plains,1  
  East ,1             Brook,1             borough,1             Heights,1 
  Mount ,1            Hill,2              mouth,1               Crossing,1
  Upper ,1            Iron,1              field,1               Cove,1    
  Lower ,1            Willow,1            crest,1               Valley,1

Important:

Pay attention to spaces and empty strings in part1.csv and part4.csv (i.e. New, Bay,1, , 50, etc.)
All names are used verbatim, therefore adjectival modifiers should include a trailing space, appended generics should include a leading space and an empty string means that the corresponding name part will be omitted.

Step 2 Launch the app

The application is distributed as a portable Windows release available in the Releases section.
It includes precompiled Lua binaries, the NML compiler and other required dependencies, and does not require installation.

Extract the contents of Town_Names_NML_Generator-winx64-portable.zip
and start the program by running START.bat.

Step 3 GRF parameters

The fields inside GRF parameters define values that are inserted into the NewGRF header.
The basics are explained below; for more details, see NML Tutorial: Starting an NML file.

Note: Required fields are marked with *. All other fields are optional.

Grf ID
GRFID is a four-byte string that uniquely identifies your NewGRF.
If two NewGRFs share the same GRFID, only one can be loaded in-game. It can also cause issues when uploading to the in-game content manager.

Examples of valid GRFID (a backslash indicates that the following two characters represent one byte, i.e. two hexadecimal digits):

SF\1A\01, HTT\1F, OTTD, etc.

For convenience, you can use the button next to the input field to generate a random GRFID that is very likely to be unique (it's chosen from 2554 possible combinations).

More details: TT-Wiki: Grfid

Version
The version number of your NewGRF. When updating your NewGRF, keep the same GRFID and increase this value with each release.

Min. ver.
The minimum compatible version. Set this equal to the current version number when backward compatibility is broken, meaning that savegames created with older versions will no longer recognize this NewGRF as compatible.
If you are unsure, leave the value at 1.
More details: TT-Wiki: Starting an NML file and TT-Wiki: NewGRF compatibility

NewGRF name
The name displayed in the NewGRF Settings menu.

Menu label
The name displayed in the World Generation menu.

NewGRF url (optional)
Optional, but useful.
Typically a link to your project's GitHub repository or TT-Forums thread.

Description (optional)
The description shown in the NewGRF list in the main menu.
For information on special formatting and tags, see TT-Wiki: Language files

Step 4 Town names

This is the main part of the application. Here, you load your input data and compile it into a *.grf file.

Load data

To load a list of names, use the Load data button or simply drag and drop a file onto the dialog window.

Because the example town name set consists of four parts, add three additional tabs using the Add button, then load part2.csv, part3.csv, and part4.csv into them.
If a part is not needed, it can be removed using the Remove button. If only one part exists, the Remove button clears the current list instead.

Note: When using a single list of complete names, you only need one tab. No additional parts are required.

The loaded data is displayed in a read-only table. You can sort the entries by Name or by Probability (any changes must be made in external software on the original source files):

Generate NML & Compile

There are two export options:

  1. NML code only use this if you prefer to compile the code yourself. Follow the instructions here:
    NML Tutorial: Compiler.

  2. NML code + compilation generates the NML code and compiles it into a GRF file using the included NML compiler.

If all required fields are filled in correctly (you will be warned about missing parameters), and if more than one list of name parts is used, you will be asked to assign weighted probabilies to each part, just as you did for the individual names in Step 1:

The application then generates the following output in the root folder (next to START.bat):

  • example_town_names.nml (the source code file; the filename is derived from the NewGRF name field)
  • english.lng in the lang subfolder

The compilation step produces an additional file, the *.grf file that is used by the game.

  • example_town_names.grf

The compilation step may take a few seconds. Please wait while the following indicator is displayed:

If generation and compilation are successful, the following dialog appears:

Note: If an error occurs, you will be prompted to check nmlc_log.txt in the application's root folder. This file usually contains a description of the problem.

You can then copy the GRF file into OpenTTD's user files directory typically
C:\Users\<name>\Documents\OpenTTD\newgrf.
Enable it in NewGRF Settings within the game. If it does not appear in the list, click Rescan files.
